‚úÖ üî∞ Beginner-Level React Interview Questions (Cleaned & Arranged)
1. What is React?

React is a JavaScript library used to build UI using components.

2. What is JSX?

JSX = JavaScript + HTML.
It must return one parent element.

3. What is a Component?

Component = reusable UI block.
Types: Functional component (modern), Class component (old).

4. What are Props?

Props = data passed from parent ‚Üí child.
Props are read-only.

5. What is State?

State = component data that can change.

6. Difference between Props & State
Props	State
Read-only	Mutable
Passed from parent	Stored inside component
Cannot change	Can change via setState/useState
7. What is useState()?

React hook to store and update data.

8. What is useEffect()?

Handles side effects ‚Üí API calls, timers, subscriptions.

9. What is Virtual DOM?

A lightweight copy of Real DOM; React updates only changed parts.

10. What is One-way Data Flow?

Data flows parent ‚Üí child only.

11. What are Keys in React Lists?

Keys help React identify which item changed in a list.

12. What are Controlled Components?

Form inputs controlled by React state.

13. What are Uncontrolled Components?

Form inputs controlled by DOM (using useRef).

14. What is Conditional Rendering?

Rendering UI based on condition:
{isLoggedIn ? <Home/> : <Login/>}

15. What is Fragment <>?</>?

Wrapper without creating an extra <div>.

16. What is Lifting State Up?

Moving state from child ‚Üí parent to share data.

‚úÖ ‚ö° Medium-Level React Interview Questions (Cleaned)
17. What is Reconciliation?

React‚Äôs process of comparing old vs new Virtual DOM and updating only changes.

18. What are React Hooks? Why introduced?

Hooks provide state & lifecycle features in functional components.
Introduced to replace complex class components.

19. Rules of Hooks

Call hooks at top level

Call hooks only inside functional components

20. What is useRef()?

Used to access DOM elements or store values without re-render.

21. Difference between useRef() and createRef()?
useRef	createRef
Value persists across renders	Creates new ref on each render
Used in functional components	Used in class components
22. What is useReducer()?

Alternative to useState for complex logic.

23. What is Context API?

Used to avoid prop drilling and share global data.

24. What is Prop Drilling? How to fix?

Passing props through multiple components unnecessarily.
Fix using: Context API / Redux / Zustand

25. What is React.memo()?

Prevents re-render if props do not change.
Used for optimization.

26. What is useCallback()?

Memoizes a function.

27. What is useMemo()?

Memoizes a heavy calculation.

Difference:

useCallback ‚Üí returns a function

useMemo ‚Üí returns a value

28. How does React batching work?

React combines multiple setState updates into one render.

29. What are Error Boundaries?

Components that catch JavaScript errors.
Works only in class components.

30. What is React Fiber?

Internal engine that improves rendering & scheduling.

31. What is Lazy Loading?

Loading components only when needed.

32. What is Code Splitting?

Breaking bundle into smaller chunks using React.lazy + Suspense.

33. What is React Router?

Library used for navigation and routing.

34. What is Redux?

State management library for large applications.

35. Difference between CSR and SSR?
CSR	SSR
Browser renders pages	Server renders HTML
Slow first load	Fast first load
Used in React apps	Used in Next.js


